  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the choice between Git rebase and squash merge is not a matter of personal preference but a critical decision impacting team collaboration and workflow efficiency. It contrasts rebase’s granular history control (risking conflicts and broken collaboration features) with squash merge’s simplicity and preservation of commit integrity, favoring the latter for its lower risk and better support for code review. Framed as a \"deathmatch,\" the analysis targets software engineers and teams, using metaphors like \"black belt in git fu\" to highlight the skill required for rebase. The core thesis advocates for squash merge as the default for most teams, emphasizing simplicity, reduced errors, and collaboration-friendly outcomes over rebase’s complexity.",
